<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s how a merger works. Some public=
 company is trading at $20 per share. Another company wants to buy it. The =
buyer goes to the target company=E2=80=99s board of directors and offers to=
 pay, say, $28 per share in cash for all of the target=E2=80=99s shares. Th=
e target=E2=80=99s board thinks about it and decides that this is=C2=A0pret=
ty good: $28 is a good result for shareholders, and a 40% premium to the pr=
ice today. So the board says yes, and the buyer and the target sign a merge=
r agreement.=C2=A0</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then the target=E2=80=
=99s shareholders get to vote on the deal. This is ordinarily just a majori=
ty vote<a href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important;=
 display: inline-block;"> <span>[1]</span> </a>: If 51% of the shares vote =
in favor of the deal and 49% vote against, the deal passes. And a merger is=
 binding on all of the shareholders. If you think that the company is actua=
lly worth $40 per share and you don=E2=80=99t want to sell at $28, you can =
vote against the deal, but if a majority of the shares vote in favor then t=
he merger will close and everyone=E2=80=99s shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0including=
 yours =E2=80=94=C2=A0will automatically be sold to the buyer for $28.</p> =
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You might dislike this. You might dislike it f=
or the simple reason that you think the company is worth more than $28, but=
 you might also have concerns about fairness. There might be conflicts of i=
nterest in the deal: The buyer might have teamed up with the chief executiv=
e officer or=C2=A0a controlling shareholder of the company to make its bid,=
 or the buyer might=C2=A0<em>be=C2=A0</em>the CEO or controlling shareholde=
r, and you might worry that the board gave the buyer a sweetheart deal rath=
er than trying to maximize value for shareholders.</p> <p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">And so Delaware law<a href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tr=
ansparent !important; display: inline-block;"> <span>[2]</span> </a> gives =
you a safety valve.=C2=A0If you don=E2=80=99t like the deal price, you can =
demand =E2=80=9Cappraisal=E2=80=9D: You can go to court and say =E2=80=9Cth=
ey sold my shares for $28, but really they=E2=80=99re worth $40, and that=
=E2=80=99s unfair.=E2=80=9D And if a judge agrees with you, she can make th=
e buyer pay you $40 instead of $28. (Only the shareholders who demanded app=
raisal=C2=A0get the $40, though; everyone else is stuck with the $28.<a hre=
f=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inl=
ine-block;"> <span>[3]</span> </a>=C2=A0She will also make the buyer pay yo=
u=C2=A0<em>interest=C2=A0</em>on the extra money, at an oddly high statutor=
y rate, which makes this an even better=C2=A0deal for you.) But you put you=
rself entirely in the hands of the judge: If she agrees with you that the c=
ompany is worth $40, you get $40; if she agrees with the buyer that it=E2=
=80=99s worth $28, you get $28; if she thinks =E2=80=9Cactually this compan=
y is only worth $15 per share,=E2=80=9D then you get only $15=C2=A0and wish=
 that you had taken the $28.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A very styliz=
ed history of appraisal is that, for a while, =E2=80=9Cappraisal arbitrage=
=E2=80=9D was a big business: Hedge funds would buy shares of companies tha=
t they thought were selling themselves too cheaply, they would demand appra=
isal, they would make arguments about (1) the unfairness of the deal proces=
s and (2) the high intrinsic value of the target company, courts would ofte=
n award them more money than the deal price (with interest), and they would=
 make a nice living.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then, around 2017=
, appraisal arbitrage stopped being so attractive.<a href=3D"#footnote-4" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"> <span>=
[4]</span> </a> Courts in Delaware decided that things had gotten out of ha=
nd, so:</p> <ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin:=
 16px 0;"> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They started deferring more to=
 deal prices: The assumption is that if a company runs any sort of reasonab=
ly competent deal process to sell itself, and the highest bid it gets is fo=
r $28, then the company can=E2=80=99t be worth $40. If the company was wort=
h $40, someone would have paid $40.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
They started deferring more to the <em>unaffected=C2=A0</em>price of the co=
mpany. If the company was trading at $20 per share, and it agreed to a merg=
er at $28 per share, that suggests that the company probably isn=E2=80=99t =
worth=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>than $28, but it doesn=E2=80=99t prove that i=
t=E2=80=99s worth $28, either. The buyer might be overpaying. Or it might b=
e paying for synergies =E2=80=94=C2=A0benefits from combining the target=E2=
=80=99s business with the buyer=E2=80=99s =E2=80=94=C2=A0which are not part=
 of the value of the target and so can=E2=80=99t be awarded in appraisal. T=
he buyer can now argue in court =E2=80=9Cactually this company is worth $20=
, as you can tell because=C2=A0<em>that was its stock price</em>, and we pa=
id $28 because of generosity and overconfidence and synergies.=E2=80=9D And=
 the court will give the shareholders $20, not $28.</li> </ul> <p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Notice that these are both essentially efficient-markets a=
rguments: Courts started saying =E2=80=9Clook, the stock market is good evi=
dence of actual value, and a public merger process is good evidence of actu=
al value, and both of them are better than our guess at value, so we=E2=80=
=99re going to rely more on markets to figure out the value.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=
</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the golden age of appraisal arbitrage,=
 you could sue for appraisal and (1) probably get paid more than the merger=
 price and (2) almost certainly not get paid=C2=A0<em>less</em>. In the new=
, post-2017 age, if you sue for appraisal you (1) probably don=E2=80=99t ge=
t paid more than the deal price and (2) have a real risk of getting paid le=
ss. In recent cases, shareholders have more often gotten less than the deal=
 price than more.<a href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;"> <span>[5]</span> </a></p> <p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">So appraisal became considerably less attractive as a strat=
egy.=C2=A0If you look at the deal price for a company and build your own di=
scounted cash flow model and conclude that, on reasonable assumptions, the =
company is actually worth $40, you won=E2=80=99t bother: A court is just no=
t that likely to defer to your discounted cash flow model, but will instead=
 consider more objective facts like =E2=80=9Cthe stock was trading at $20 b=
efore the deal was announced=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthe best deal the board =
could get was for $28.=E2=80=9D Your spreadsheet with =E2=80=9C$40=E2=80=9D=
 at the bottom can=E2=80=99t compete.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But =
appraisal still exists, and there are still cases, and sometimes they pay o=
ut. Sometimes the deal process is so conflicted, and the shareholder=E2=80=
=99s discounted cash flow model is so compelling, that the court decides th=
